  "Chinese astronomers could see better than modern telescopes": "",
  "The 1054 record is unrelated to the Crab Nebula": "",
  "The 1054 'guest star' was a supernova — the explosion that created the Crab Nebula. Chinese and Japanese records of its position, brightness, and duration help modern astronomers understand the supernova's energy and the nebula's age. This is a beautiful example of ancient and modern science complementing each other.": "",
  "The Antikythera mechanism, an ancient Greek device recovered from a shipwreck, was found to predict eclipses and planetary positions. What does this tell us about ancient Greek technology?": "",
  "The Greeks knew nothing about astronomy": "",
  "The Greeks had far more sophisticated mechanical engineering and astronomical knowledge than previously thought": "",
  "The device was placed on the shipwreck by modern divers": "",
  "Ancient Greeks had electronic computers": "",
  "The Antikythera mechanism (c. 100 BCE) is the world's first known analog computer. Its intricate gear system modeled solar and lunar eclipses, the Metonic cycle, and possibly planetary positions — demonstrating a level of mechanical sophistication not seen again for over a millennium.": "",
  "Polynesian navigators crossed thousands of miles of open Pacific Ocean using star positions, ocean currents, and wave patterns — without any instruments. What does this demonstrate about traditional astronomical knowledge?": "",
